ypoparathyroidism","Hypothyroidism","Inflammatory bowel disease","Primary hypoaldosteronism"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of kidney stones, particularly calcium oxalate stones. This occurs through several mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFat malabsorption leads to increased binding of calcium to fatty acids in the intestinal lumen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReduced calcium binding to oxalate in the gut results in increased free oxalate absorption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic diarrhoea causes volume depletion and concentrated urine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E actually decreases stone risk by reducing urinary calcium excretion. Conversely, hyperparathyroidism is associated with an increased risk of stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hypoaldosteronism\u003C/strong\u003E does not significantly affect stone formation. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egrowth hormone deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E have no direct effect on stone formation risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inflammatory bowel disease increases risk of calcium oxalate stones due to fat malabsorption and increased oxalate absorption","Hypoparathyroidism decreases urinary calcium excretion and thus reduces stone risk"],"references":["Bianchi L, Gaiani F, Bizzarri B, Minelli R, Cortegoso Valdivia P, Leandro G, Di Mario F, De\u0027 Angelis GL, Ruberto C. Renal lithiasis and inflammatory bowel diseases, an update on pediatric population. Acta Biomed. 2018 Dec 17;89(9-S):76-80. doi: 10.23750/abm.v89i9-S.7908. PMID: 30561398; PMCID: PMC6502195.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T17:32:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T17:32:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7780"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64466"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4